<DOC><DOCNO> AP880621-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0013EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-ElderlyShooting     06-21 0292</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Elderly Shooting,290</SECOND><HEAD>One Killed, Another Wounded in Hostage-Taking at Senior CitizensBuilding</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 64-year-old man who said he was upset aboutdrug trafficking was charged Monday with murder after two elderlyneighbors in his senior citizens apartment building were shot and athird was held hostage for several hours, police said.   Nathaniel Mayo was accused of shooting two of his neighbors inthe head and leaving them for dead, police said.   Assistant Police Chief Isaac Fullwood said the two women werefound in a third-floor hallway at about 9:30 a.m. A 65-year-oldwoman was pronounced dead at the scene and a 64-year-old woman washospitalized in critical condition at The Washington HospitalCenter, Fullwood said.   Another resident, Neva Williams, 75, was held hostage inWilliams' fourth floor apartment as officers evacuated dozens ofother residents from the 123-unit complex, police said.   Mayo summoned WJLA-TV reporter Del Walters to the scene, andWalters, who arrived about 3:30 p.m., eventually persuaded Mayo togive himself up, officials said.   Walters said Mayo claimed to have met him last week at theDistrict Building where he threatened to do ``something drastic''if measures were not taken to stop drug trafficking in hisneighborhood. Walters said he only vaguely remembered theconversation.   Mayo told police Monday night that he has terminal cancer and``nothing to lose.''   According to police, Mayo lived in a third-floor apartmentadjacent to the apartments of the two women who were shot.Neighbors said the dead woman frequently did Mayo's groceryshopping.   Police did not release the names of the two shooting victims bylate Monday, but residents of the building identified the deadwoman as Carrie Walls. The injured woman was identified byresidents as Emma Waldo.</TEXT></DOC>